<td align="center">
<div class="poemtitle">At St. Albans Churchyard</div> 
<br>
<a class="byline" href="javascript:goauthor('hobson')">by Juleigh Howard-Hobson</a> <br>
<br>
<br>
<table cellpadding="20" cellspacing="0"><tr><td valign="top">
Old headstones—namelessly eroded—green <br>
and grey with speckled moss in the sudden light<br>
that fell after this morning’s rain. The bright<br>
sparkle of the sun reflected in between<br>
these markers, where crevassed droplets fell<br>
on webs, wet-laden now and spider-less.<br>
&nbsp;<br>
So do our lives always come down to this:<br>
damp stones in sunny boneyards. Nothing else.<br>
&nbsp;<br><br>
<FONT SIZE=-1>(first appeared in <EM>The Hyper Texts</EM>)<br>
</td>
<td align="right"><img src="images/stalbans.jpg"><br><span class="byartist">C. D. Russell</span></td>
</tr></table>
</td>
</tr>
